<h2><a name="string_stream_operators" id="string_stream_operators">String Stream Operators</a></h2>
<div class="level2">

<p>
Syntax:
</p>
<pre class="c code c++" style="font-family:monospace;">    <span class="co2">#include &lt;sstream&gt;</span>
    operator<span class="sy0">&lt;&lt;</span>
    operator<span class="sy0">&gt;&gt;</span></pre>
<p>

Like C++_I/O_Streams, the simplest way to use string streams is to take
advantage of the overloaded « and » operators.
The « operator inserts data into the stream. For example:
</p>
<pre class="c code c++" style="font-family:monospace;">    stream1 <span class="sy0">&lt;&lt;</span> <span class="st0">&quot;hello&quot;</span> <span class="sy0">&lt;&lt;</span> i<span class="sy0">;</span></pre>
<p>

This example inserts the string “hello” and the variable i into stream1. In
contrast, the » operator extracts data out of a string stream:
</p>
<pre class="c code c++" style="font-family:monospace;">    stream1 <span class="sy0">&gt;&gt;</span> i<span class="sy0">;</span></pre>
<p>

This code reads a value from stream1 and assigns the variable i that value.
</p>

<p>
Related Topics: <a href="../start" class="wikilink1" title="io:start">C++ I/O Streams</a>
</p>

</div>
